  Assessment — greenfield vs partially built

  Roughly two-thirds greenfield, one-third partially-built-but-fragmented. Everything on the Google Fonts axis is greenfield:
  there is no fetch, no .ttf cache, and no CTFontManagerRegisterFontsForURL registration seam — and the existing font
  machinery is the local-directory-scanner model you're explicitly replacing, so it's discard-not-extend. Above that seam,
  though, the style-application layer is genuinely partially built: Stylish.twk already turns hex into a Color and
  name/size/bold/italic into an NSFont, the cOLOr hex registry is established and consumed, and decomposed font attributes
  are already partially understood by setFont. The real non-greenfield work isn't writing that layer from scratch — it's
  consolidation: four competing font-definition formats need to collapse onto the agreed family/size/bold/italic
  decomposition, setFont needs to read family, and the color path needs the #-handling confirmed against your updated
  ParseXML grammar. Net: build the fetch+registration plumbing fresh; refactor (don't rebuild) the style/registry layer onto
  the agreed format.
